{"title_page": "Venus (Shocking Blue song)", "text_new": "{{Infobox song\n| name       = Venus\n| cover      = Venus_-_Shocking_Blue.jpeg\n| alt        =\n| caption    = \n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Shocking Blue]]\n| album      = \n| B-side     = Hot Sand\n| released   = {{Start date|1969|7|df=yes}}\n| format     = [[7-inch single|7-inch]]\n| recorded   =\n| studio     = Soundpush, [[Blaricum]], Netherlands\n| genre      = [[Country rock]]<ref>{{cite AV media notes|title= Venus/Dancing on a Saturday Night/Beautiful Sunday |others= Shocking Blue/Barry Blue/Daniel Boone |year= 1989 |url= https://www.discogs.com/release/4835144-Venus-Dancing-On-A-Saturday-Night-Beautiful-Sunday/images |accessdate= 17 October 2019 |type= liner notes |publisher= Old Gold}}</ref>\n| length     = 3:06\n| label      = Pink Elephant\n| writer     = [[Robbie van Leeuwen]]<ref name=GEMA>{{cite web |url=https://online.gema.de/werke/detailPage.do?dbkey=26326293&title=VENUS&pdf=false |title=VENUS|work=GEMA \u2013 Members \u2014 Online Database \u2013 Musical Works |publisher=[[GEMA (German organization)|GEMA]] |accessdate=9 May 2012}}</ref>\n| producer   =\n* Robbie van Leeuwen\n* [[Jerry Ross (record producer)|Jerry Ross]]\n| prev_title = Lucy Brown Is Back in Town\n| prev_year  = 1968\n| next_title = [[Mighty Joe]]\n| next_year  = 1969\n| misc       = {{External music video|header=Audio|{{youtube|Dg-UiOSjJeM|\"Venus\"}}}}\n}}\n\n\"'''Venus'''\" is a song by Dutch [[Rock music|rock]] band [[Shocking Blue]], initially released as a single in the Netherlands in the summer of 1969. Written by [[Robbie van Leeuwen]], the song topped the charts in nine countries. In 1981, it was used to open the \"[[Stars on 45 (song)|Stars on 45]]\" medley.<ref>{{cite magazine |last=Grein |first=Paul |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=oCQEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PT5&dq=Medley |title=Chart Beat |magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |volume=98 |issue=36 |date=6 September 1986 |page=6 |issn=0006-2510 |accessdate=21 August 2019 |via=[[Google Books]]}}</ref> In 1986, English girl group [[Bananarama]] covered \"Venus\" for their third studio album, ''[[True Confessions (album)|True Confessions]]'', reaching number one in six countries. The composition has been featured in numerous films, television shows and commercials, and covered dozens of times by artists around the world.\n\n==Shocking Blue (original)==\n[[File:Popgroep Shocking Blue gaf persconferentie in verband met succes van plaat Ve, Bestanddeelnr 923-1956.jpg|thumb|left|Shocking Blue in 1970]] \n\n===Background===\n\"Venus\" was issued in the Netherlands in July 1969 as a single, backed with \"Hot Sand\", on the Pink Elephant label. The song peaked at number three on the [[Dutch Top 40]] on 12 July 1969, and remained at that position for a total of five weeks. Later that year, \"Venus\" was issued in several European countries and other worldwide nations. In the United States, \"Venus\" reached number one on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] on 7 February 1970. On 28 January 1970, it was certified gold by the [[Recording Industry Association of America]] (RIAA) for sales in excess of one million copies in the United States.<ref name=\"RIAA\"/> Worldwide, the single has sold over 7.5 million copies.<ref>{{cite magazine |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Ig8EAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA40&dq=Venus |title=Shocking Blue: huge success around world |magazine=Billboard |volume=84 |issue=49 |date=2 December 1972 |page=40 |issn=0006-2510 |accessdate=21 August 2019 |via=Google Books}}</ref> \n\n\"Venus\" was included as a bonus track on the 1989 CD reissue of the group's second studio album, ''[[At Home (Shocking Blue album)|At Home]]'', originally released in 1969.\n\nThe song's lead vocals are performed by [[Mariska Veres]]. The music is from \"The Banjo Song\" by Tim Rose and the Big 3 with new lyrics by [[Robbie van Leeuwen]], the band's guitarist, [[sitar]]ist and background vocalist, who also produced along with record producer [[Jerry Ross (record producer)|Jerry Ross]]. Van Leeuwen originally miswrote the line \"...the ''goddess'' on the mountain top...\" as \"...the ''godness'' on the mountain top...\", so Veres sang it this way on the recording of the song. This was corrected in later versions.{{cn|date=June 2017}} The [[Hohner|Hohner electric piano]] on the single was played by [[:nl:Cees Schrama|Cees Schrama]].{{cn|date=June 2017}}\n\nVan Leeuwen was inspired by \"The Banjo Song\", a composition by [[Tim Rose]], for [[The Big 3 (folk_group)|The Big 3]], that set [[Stephen Foster]]'s lyrics to \"[[Oh! Susanna]]\" to a completely new melody.{{cn|date=December 2018}}\n\n===BHF/Don Pablo's Animals remixes {{anchor|bhf|don_pablos_animals}}===\n\"Venus\" was remixed and re-released by dance producers The BHF (Bisiach Hornbostel Ferrucci) Team in May 1990. Titled \"Venus '90\", the remix featured a [[hip house]] rhythm and [[Sampling (music)|samples]]. \"Venus '90\" reached number 78 on the [[UK Singles Chart]] and number 49 on the Australian [[ARIA Charts|ARIA Singles Chart]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://australian-charts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Shocking+Blue&titel=Venus+%2790&cat=s |title=Shocking Blue \u2013 Venus '90 |website=australian-charts.com |accessdate=21 August 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"UK chart Shocking Blue\"/> An instrumental version was also released independently under the producer's alias, Don Pablo's Animals, without referencing Shocking Blue. The instrumental version became the highest-charting version of the song, peaking at number four on the UK Singles Chart.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.officialcharts.com/artist/26206/don-pablos-animals/ |title=Don Pablo's Animals: Artist Chart History |publisher=Official Charts Company |accessdate=21 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Charts===\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n\n====Weekly charts====\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"| Chart (1969\u201370)\n! scope=\"col\"| Peak<br/>position\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Australia ([[Kent Music Report]])<ref>{{harvnb|Kent|1993|p=273}}</ref>\n| 1\n|-\n{{single chart|Austria|2|artist=Shocking Blue|song=Venus|rowheader=true|accessdate=21 August 2019}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Flanders|1|artist=Shocking Blue|song=Venus|rowheader=true|accessdate=21 August 2019}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Wallonia|1|artist=Shocking Blue|song=Venus|rowheader=true|accessdate=21 August 2019}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Canadatopsingles|1|chartid=6118|rowheader=true|accessdate=21 August 2019|refname=\"CAN-Shocking-Blue\"}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Finland ([[The Official Finnish Charts|Suomen virallinen lista]])<ref name=\"Finland\">{{cite book |last=Pennanen |first=Timo |title=Sis\u00e4lt\u00e4\u00e4 hitin \u2013 levyt ja esitt\u00e4j\u00e4t Suomen musiikkilistoilla vuodesta 1972 |language=Finnish |edition=1st |location=Helsinki |publisher=[[Otava (publisher)|Kustannusosakeyhti\u00f6 Otava]] |year=2006 |isbn=978-951-1-21053-5}}</ref>\n| 4\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| France ([[Institut fran\u00e7ais d'opinion publique|IFOP]])<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.infodisc.fr/Chanson_Number1_60.php |title=Toutes les Chansons N\u00b0 1 des Ann\u00e9es 60's |website=InfoDisc |language=French |accessdate=21 August 2019}}</ref>\n| 1\n|-\n{{single chart|Ireland2|10|song=Venus|rowheader=true|accessdate=21 August 2019|refname=\"Ireland\"}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Dutch40|3|artist=Shocking Blue|rowheader=true|accessdate=21 August 2019}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Dutch100|2|artist=Shocking Blue|song=Venus|rowheader=true|accessdate=21 August 2019}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| New Zealand (''[[New Zealand Listener|Listener]]'')<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.flavourofnz.co.nz/index.php?qpageID=search%20listener&qsongid=1886#n_view_location |title=Search listener |website=Flavour of New Zealand |accessdate=21 August 2019}}</ref>\n| 1\n|-\n{{single chart|Norway|2|artist=Shocking Blue|song=Venus|rowheader=true|accessdate=21 August 2019}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| South Africa ([[Springbok Radio]])<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rock.co.za/files/springbok_top_20_(S).html |title=SA Charts 1965\u20131989 (As presented on Springbok Radio/Radio Orion) \u2013 Acts S |website=The South African Rock Encyclopedia |accessdate=5 September 2018}}</ref>\n| 1\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Spain ([[Productores de M\u00fasica de Espa\u00f1a|AFYVE]])<ref name=\"AFYVE\">{{cite book |last=Salaverrie |first=Fernando |title=S\u00f3lo \u00e9xitos: a\u00f1o a a\u00f1o, 1959\u20132002 |language=Spanish |edition=1st |location=Madrid |publisher=[[Sociedad General de Autores y Editores|Fundaci\u00f3n Autor/SGAE]] |date=September 2005 |isbn=84-8048-639-2}}</ref>\n| 1\n|-\n{{single chart|Switzerland|1|artist=Shocking Blue|song=Venus|rowheader=true|accessdate=21 August 2019}}\n|-\n{{single chart|UKsinglesbyname|8|artist=Shocking Blue|artistid=13890|rowheader=true|accessdate=21 August 2019|refname=\"UK chart Shocking Blue\"}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Billboardhot100|1|artist=The Shocking Blue|rowheader=true|accessdate=21 August 2019}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| US ''[[Cashbox (magazine)|Cash Box]]'' Top 100<ref>{{cite web |url=https://cashboxmagazine.com/archives/70s_files/19700214.html |title=Cash Box Top 100 Singles \u2013 Week ending February 14, 1970 |work=[[Cashbox (magazine)|Cash Box]] |accessdate=21 August 2019}}</ref>\n| 1\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| US ''[[Record World]]'' 100 Top Pops<ref>{{cite magazine |url=https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Record-World/70s/70/RW-1970-01-24.pdf |title=100 Top Pops |magazine=[[Record World]] |volume=24 |issue=1180 |date=24 January 1970 |page=43 |issn=0034-1622 |accessdate=21 August 2019 |via=American Radio History}}</ref>\n| 1\n|-\n{{single chart|West Germany|2|songid=116|artist=Shocking Blue|song=Venus|rowheader=true|accessdate=21 August 2019}}\n|}\n{{col-2}}\n\n====Year-end charts====\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"| Chart (1970)\n! scope=\"col\"| Position\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Australia (Kent Music Report)<ref>{{cite web |url=https://australian-charts.com/forum.asp?todo=viewthread&id=40276 |title=Forum \u2013 ARIA Charts: Special Occasion Charts \u2013 Top 100 End of Year AMR Charts \u2013 1970s |website=australian-charts.com |accessdate=21 August 2019}}</ref>\n| 19\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Austria (\u00d63 Austria Top 40)<ref>{{cite web |url=https://austriancharts.at/year.asp?cat=s&id=1970 |title=Jahreshitparade Singles 1970 |language=German |website=austriancharts.at |accessdate=21 August 2019}}</ref>\n| 8\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Canada Top Singles (''RPM'')<ref>{{cite magazine |url=http://www.bac-lac.gc.ca/eng/discover/films-videos-sound-recordings/rpm/Pages/image.aspx?Image=nlc008388.3740&URLjpg=http%3a%2f%2fwww.collectionscanada.gc.ca%2fobj%2f028020%2ff4%2fnlc008388.3740.gif&Ecopy=nlc008388.3740 |title=RPM's Top 100 of 1970 |magazine=RPM |volume=14 |issue=20/21 |date=9 January 1971 |page=13 |issn=0315-5994 |accessdate=21 August 2019 |via=Library and Archives Canada}}</ref>\n| 17\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Netherlands (Dutch Top 40)<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.top40.nl/bijzondere-lijsten/top-100-jaaroverzichten/1970 |title=Top 100-Jaaroverzicht van 1970 |language=Dutch |publisher=Dutch Top 40 |accessdate=21 August 2019}}</ref>\n| 31\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Netherlands (Single Top 100)<ref>{{cite web |url=https://dutchcharts.nl/jaaroverzichten.asp?year=1970&cat=s |title=Jaaroverzichten \u2013 Single 1970 |language=Dutch |website=dutchcharts.nl |accessdate=21 August 2019}}</ref>\n| 28\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| South Africa (Springbok Radio)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rock.co.za/files/sahits_1970.html |title=Top 20 Hit Singles of 1970 |website=The South African Rock Encyclopedia |accessdate=2 September 2018}}</ref>\n| 7\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| US ''Billboard'' Hot 100<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.musicoutfitters.com/topsongs/1970.htm |title=Top 100 Hits of 1970/Top 100 Songs of 1970 |website=Music Outfitters |accessdate=21 August 2019}}</ref>\n| 33\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| US ''Cash Box'' Top 100<ref>{{cite web |url=https://cashboxmagazine.com/archives/70s_files/1970YESP.html |title=The Cash Box Year-End Charts: 1970 \u2013 Top 100 Pop Singles |work=Cash Box |date=26 December 1970 |accessdate=21 August 2019}}</ref>\n| 6\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| West Germany (Official German Charts)<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.offiziellecharts.de/charts/single-jahr/for-date-1970 |title=Top 100 Single-Jahrescharts \u2013 1970 |language=German |publisher=Offizielle Deutsche Charts |accessdate=21 August 2019}}</ref>\n| 23\n|}\n\n===Certifications===\n{{Certification Table Top}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=United States|artist=Shocking Blue|title=Venus|award=Gold|type=single|relyear=1970|certyear=1970|date=28 January 1970|accessdate=21 August 2019|refname=\"RIAA\"}}\n{{Certification Table Bottom|nosales=yes}}\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Bananarama version==\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = Venus\n| cover      = Banana_v.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Bananarama]]\n| album      = [[True Confessions (album)|True Confessions]]\n| B-side     = White Train\n| released   = 19 May 1986\n| format     =\n* [[7-inch single|7-inch]]\n* [[12-inch single|12-inch]]\n| recorded   = December 1985\n| studio     = [[Odyssey Studios|Odyssey]], London\n| genre      = \n*[[Dance-pop]]<ref>{{cite book|first= James |last= Arena |year= 2017 |title= Europe's Stars of '80s Dance Pop: 32 International Music Legends Discuss Their Careers |chapter= Appendix: The Record Shop\u2013Noteworthy Tracks |page= 225\u2013230 |publisher= [[McFarland & Company]] |isbn= 978-1-4766-7142-0 |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=zMYtDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA225}}</ref>\n*[[hi-NRG]]<ref>{{cite web|title= Bananarama: Pop in the First Degree |work= M Magazine |date= 4 November 2013 |accessdate= 17 October 2019 |url= http://www.m-magazine.co.uk/features/bananaram-pop-first-degree/}}</ref>\n| length     = 3:50\n| label      = [[London Records|London]]\n| writer     = [[Robbie van Leeuwen]]\n| producer   = [[Stock Aitken Waterman]]\n| prev_title = [[Do Not Disturb (Bananarama song)|Do Not Disturb]]\n| prev_year  = 1985\n| next_title = [[More Than Physical]]\n| next_year  = 1986\n| misc       = {{External music video|{{youtube|d4-1ASpdT1Y|\"Venus\"}}}}\n}}\n\n===Background===\n\"Venus\" had been a part of Bananarama's repertoire for several years before they actually recorded it. The group's three members, [[Sara Dallin]], [[Siobhan Fahey]], and [[Keren Woodward]], had the idea of turning the song into a [[dance music]] tune, but they were met with resistance from their producers at the time, [[Jolley & Swain|Steve Jolley and Tony Swain]]. Bananarama brought the idea to the production trio of [[Stock Aitken Waterman]], and it became Bananarama's first collaboration with them.\n\nDallin, Fahey, and Woodward had nearly completed recording their third studio album, ''[[True Confessions (album)|True Confessions]]'', with Jolley and Swain. Stock, Aitken and Waterman also resisted the idea because they believed that \"Venus\" would not make a good dance record. After persistence by the women, SAW relented. Bananarama's \"Venus\" peaked at number one in the United States, Australia, Finland, New Zealand, Switzerland, and South Africa, while reaching number two in Germany and the top 10 in Austria, Belgium, Canada, France, Netherlands, Norway, Spain, Sweden and their native United Kingdom (number eight on the [[UK Singles Chart]]). It also topped the US [[Dance Club Songs|Hot Dance/Disco]] chart for two weeks.<ref>{{cite book |last=Whitburn |first=Joel |authorlink=Joel Whitburn |title=Hot Dance/Disco: 1974\u20132003 |publisher=Record Research |year=2004 |page=28}}</ref>\n\nThe collaboration on \"Venus\" led Bananarama and SAW to work together on the group's follow-up album ''[[Wow! (Bananarama album)|Wow!]]'' the following year.\n\nA new mix of the track appeared as B-side to the 1989 limited release \"Megarama '89\" in Germany and France.  Bananarama has since re-recorded the track for their 2001 album ''[[Exotica (Bananarama album)|Exotica]]'' and it was later [[remix]]ed by [[Marc Almond]], with re-recorded vocals, and included on their 2005 album ''[[Drama (Bananarama album)|Drama]]''.\n\n===Music video===\nThe music video, directed by [[Peter Care]], with choreography by [[Bruno Tonioli]], received extensive play on [[MTV]] and video channels across the world, and presented Bananarama in various costumes, including a [[Succubus|she-devil]], a French [[temptress]], a [[vampiress]], and several [[Greek mythology|Greek]] [[goddess]]es. In one sequence of the video, [[Sandro Botticelli]]'s painting ''[[The Birth of Venus]]'' is adapted as a ''[[tableau vivant]]''. The video marked a pivotal shift towards a more glamorous and sexual image for the girls that contrasted with the tomboyish style of their earlier work.\n\n===Track listings===\n*'''UK / US / Canadian 7-inch single'''\n''UK: London Records NANA 10 / US: London Records 886-056-7 / Canada: London Records LDS 227 / Australia: Liberation Records LS 1789''\n#\"Venus\" \u2013 3:30\n#\"White Train\" \u2013 3:50\n#:<small>S.Dallin/S. Fahey/K. Woodward/P. Bishop/P. Seymour</small>\n+ some copies released in picture disc format ''NANPD 10''\n\n*'''UK / Australian 12-inch single'''\n''UK: London Records NANX 10 / Australia: Liberation Records LMD 474''\n#\"Venus\" (extended version) \u2013 7:23\n#\"Venus\" (dub) \u2013 8:15\n#\"White Train\" \u2013 3:50\n\n*'''2nd UK 12-inch single'''\n''London Records NANXR 10''\n#\"Venus\" (the Hellfire mix) \u2013 9:20  #:<small>remixed by Ian Levine</small>\n#\"Venus\" (Hellfire dub) \u2013 6:55\n#\"White Train\" \u2013 3:50\n\n*'''3rd UK 12-inch single'''\n''London Records NAXRR 10''\n#\"Venus\" (the Fire And Brimstone mix) \u2013 6:35  #:<small>remixed by Stock, Aitken & Waterman</small>\n#\"Venus\" (Hellfire dub) \u2013 6:55\n#\"White Train\" \u2013 3:50\n\n*'''US 12-inch maxi single'''\n''London Records 886 088-1''\n#\"Venus\" (the Hellfire mix) \u2013 9:20\n#\"Venus\" (the Fire & Brimstone mix) \u2013 6:55\n#\"Venus\" (extended version) \u2013 7:23\n#\"Venus\" (dub) \u2013 8:25\n\n*'''CD video single'''\n#\"Venus\" (extended version) \u2013 7:23\n#\"True Confessions\" (edit) \u2013 4:09\n#\"[[A Trick of the Night]]\" (edit) \u2013 4:07\n#\"[[More Than Physical]]\" (U.K. single version) \u2013 3:40\n\n*'''Other versions'''\n#\"Venus\" (the Greatest Remix edit) \u2013 3:40\n#:<small>Included on the 1989 U.K. CD single \"Cruel Summer '89\", remixed by Phil Harding and Ian Curnow</small>\n#\"Venus\" (the Greatest Remix)  7:43\n#:<small>Included on the 1989 German CD single \"[[Megarama '89]]\", remixed by Phil Harding and Ian Curnow</small>\n#\"Venus\" (2001 version)\n#:<small>Included on the album ''[[Exotica (Bananarama album)|Exotica]]''</small>\n#\"Venus\" (Marc Almond's Hi-NRG Showgirls mix)  6:02\n#:<small>Included on the 2005 album ''[[Drama (Bananarama album)|Drama]]'', remixed by [[Marc Almond]]</small>\n#\"Venus\" (from the soundtrack ''Sugar & Spice: Stuck in the 80's'')\n\n===Credits and personnel===\nCredits adapted from the liner notes of ''[[True Confessions (album)|True Confessions]]''.<ref>{{cite AV media notes |title=[[True Confessions (album)|True Confessions]] |type=liner notes |others=[[Bananarama]] |publisher=[[London Records]] |year=1986 |id=RAMA 3}}</ref>\n\n* [[Stock Aitken Waterman]] \u2013 production\n* [[Matt Aitken]] \u2013 guitar\n* [[Mike Stock (musician)|Mike Stock]] \u2013 keyboards\n* Garry Hughes \u2013 keyboards\n* [[Linn 9000|A. Linn]] \u2013 drums\n* Tim Young \u2013 mastering\n\n===Charts===\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n\n====Weekly charts====\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"| Chart (1986)\n! scope=\"col\"| Peak<br/>position\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Australia ([[Kent Music Report]])<ref>{{harvnb|Kent|1993|p=25}}</ref>\n| 1\n|-\n{{single chart|Austria|7|arti