Category:1986 singles]]\n[[Category:Bananarama songs]]\n[[Category:Billboard Dance Club Songs number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Billboard Hot 100 number-one singles]]\n[[Category:English-language Dutch songs]]\n[[Category:Greco-Roman mythology in popular culture]]\n[[Category:London Records singles]]\n[[Category:Metronome Records singles]]\n[[Category:Minos EMI singles]]\n[[Category:Number-one singles in Australia]]\n[[Category:Number-one singles in Belgium]]\n[[Category:Number-one singles in Finland]]\n[[Category:Number-one singles in France]]\n[[Category:Number-one singles in New Zealand]]\n[[Category:Number-one singles in South Africa]]\n[[Category:Number-one singles in Spain]]\n[[Category:Number-one singles in Switzerland]]\n[[Category:RPM Top Singles number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Shocking Blue songs]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by Stock Aitken Waterman]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Robbie van Leeuwen]]\n[[Category:Ultratop 50 Singles (Flanders) number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Ultratop 50 Singles (Wallonia) number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Greco-Roman mythology in music]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox song\n| name       = Venus\n| cover      = Venus_-_Shocking_Blue.jpeg\n| alt        =\n| caption    = \n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Shocking Blue]]\n| album      = \n| B-side     = Hot Sand\n| released   = {{Start date|1969|7|df=yes}}\n| format     = [[7-inch single|7-inch]]\n| recorded   =\n| studio     = Soundpush, [[Blaricum]], Netherlands\n| genre      = [[Country rock]]<ref>{{cite AV media notes|title= Venus/Dancing on a Saturday Night/Beautiful Sunday |others= Shocking Blue/Barry Blue/Daniel Boone |year= 1989 |url= https://www.discogs.com/release/4835144-Venus-Dancing-On-A-Saturday-Night-Beautiful-Sunday/images |accessdate= 17 October 2019 |type= liner notes |publisher= Old Gold}}</ref>\n| length     = 3:06\n| label      = Pink Elephant\n| writer     = [[Robbie van Leeuwen]]<ref name=GEMA>{{cite web |url=https://online.gema.de/werke/detailPage.do?dbkey=26326293&title=VENUS&pdf=false |title=VENUS|work=GEMA \u2013 Members \u2014 Online Database \u2013 Musical Works |publisher=[[GEMA (German organization)|GEMA]] |accessdate=9 May 2012}}</ref>\n| producer   =\n* Robbie van Leeuwen\n* [[Jerry Ross (record producer)|Jerry Ross]]\n| prev_title = Lucy Brown Is Back in Town\n| prev_year  = 1968\n| next_title = [[Mighty Joe]]\n| next_year  = 1969\n| misc       = {{External music video|header=Audio|{{youtube|Dg-UiOSjJeM|\"Venus\"}}}}\n}}\n\n\"'''Venus'''\" is a song by Dutch [[Rock music|rock]] band [[Shocking Blue]], initially released as a single in the Netherlands in the summer of 1969. Written by [[Robbie van Leeuwen]], the song topped the charts in nine countries. In 1981, it was used to open the \"[[Stars on 45 (song)|Stars on 45]]\" medley.<ref>{{cite magazine |last=Grein |first=Paul |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=oCQEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PT5&dq=Medley |title=Chart Beat |magazine=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]] |volume=98 |issue=36 |date=6 September 1986 |page=6 |issn=0006-2510 |accessdate=21 August 2019 |via=[[Google Books]]}}</ref> In 1986, English girl group [[Bananarama]] covered \"Venus\" for their third studio album, ''[[True Confessions (album)|True Confessions]]'', reaching number one in six countries. The composition has been featured in numerous films, television shows and commercials, and covered dozens of times by artists around the world.\n\n==Shocking Blue (original)==\n[[File:Popgroep Shocking Blue gaf persconferentie in verband met succes van plaat Ve, Bestanddeelnr 923-1956.jpg|thumb|left|Shocking Blue in 1970]] \n\n===Background===\n\"Venus\" was issued in the Netherlands in July 1969 as a single, backed with \"Hot Sand\", on the Pink Elephant label. The song peaked at number three on the [[Dutch Top 40]] on 12 July 1969, and remained at that position for a total of five weeks. Later that year, \"Venus\" was issued in several European countries and other worldwide nations. In the United States, \"Venus\" reached number one on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] on 7 February 1970. On 28 January 1970, it was certified gold by the [[Recording Industry Association of America]] (RIAA) for sales in excess of one million copies in the United States.<ref name=\"RIAA\"/> Worldwide, the single has sold over 7.5 million copies.<ref>{{cite magazine |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Ig8EAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA40&dq=Venus |title=Shocking Blue: huge success around world |magazine=Billboard |volume=84 |issue=49 |date=2 December 1972 |page=40 |issn=0006-2510 |accessdate=21 August 2019 |via=Google Books}}</ref> \n\n\"Venus\" was included as a bonus track on the 1989 CD reissue of the group's second studio album, ''[[At Home (Shocking Blue album)|At Home]]'', originally released in 1969.\n\nThe song's lead vocals are performed by [[Mariska Veres]]. The music is from \"The Banjo Song\" by Tim Rose and the Big 3 with new lyrics by [[Robbie van Leeuwen]], the band's guitarist, [[sitar]]ist and background vocalist, who also produced along with record producer [[Jerry Ross (record producer)|Jerry Ross]]. Van Leeuwen originally miswrote the line \"...the ''goddess'' on the mountain top...\" as \"...the ''godness'' on the mountain top...\", so Veres sang it this way on the recording of the song. This was corrected in later versions.{{cn|date=June 2017}} The [[Hohner|Hohner electric piano]] on the single was played by [[:nl:Cees Schrama|Cees Schrama]].{{cn|date=June 2017}}\n\nVan Leeuwen was inspired by \"The Banjo Song\", a composition by [[Tim Rose]], for [[The Big 3 (folk_group)|The Big 3]], that set [[Stephen Foster]]'s lyrics to \"[[Oh! Susanna]]\" to a completely new melody.{{cn|date=December 2018}}\n\n===BHF/Don Pablo's Animals remixes {{anchor|bhf|don_pablos_animals}}===\n\"Venus\" was remixed and re-released by dance producers The BHF (Bisiach Hornbostel Ferrucci) Team in May 1990. Titled \"Venus '90\", the remix featured a [[hip house]] rhythm and [[Sampling (music)|samples]]. \"Venus '90\" reached number 78 on the [[UK Singles Chart]] and number 49 on the Australian [[ARIA Charts|ARIA Singles Chart]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://australian-charts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=Shocking+Blue&titel=Venus+%2790&cat=s |title=Shocking Blue \u2013 Venus '90 |website=australian-charts.com |accessdate=21 August 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"UK chart Shocking Blue\"/> An instrumental version was also released independently under the producer's alias, Don Pablo's Animals, without referencing Shocking Blue. The instrumental version became the highest-charting version of the song, peaking at number four on the UK Singles Chart.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.officialcharts.com/artist/26206/don-pablos-animals/ |title=Don Pablo's Animals: Artist Chart History |publisher=Official Charts Company |accessdate=21 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Charts===\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n\n====Weekly charts====\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"| Chart (1969\u201370)\n! scope=\"col\"| Peak<br/>position\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Australia ([[Kent Music Report]])<ref>{{harvnb|Kent|1993|p=273}}</ref>\n| 1\n|-\n{{single chart|Austria|2|artist=Shocking Blue|song=Venus|rowheader=true|accessdate=21 August 2019}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Flanders|1|artist=Shocking Blue|song=Venus|rowheader=true|accessdate=21 August 2019}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Wallonia|1|artist=Shocking Blue|song=Venus|rowheader=true|accessdate=21 August 2019}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Canadatopsingles|1|chartid=6118|rowheader=true|accessdate=21 August 2019|refname=\"CAN-Shocking-Blue\"}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Finland ([[The Official Finnish Charts|Suomen virallinen lista]])<ref name=\"Finland\">{{cite book |last=Pennanen |first=Timo |title=Sis\u00e4lt\u00e4\u00e4 hitin \u2013 levyt ja esitt\u00e4j\u00e4t Suomen musiikkilistoilla vuodesta 1972 |language=Finnish |edition=1st |location=Helsinki |publisher=[[Otava (publisher)|Kustannusosakeyhti\u00